Python Input
    IN Python, inpput() functions read data from keyboard as string, irrespective of whether it is enclosed with quotes('' or "") or not.
    
    Taking input from keyboard at runtime
        age=input("Enter your age:")
        print("Your age =",age);
        
    input() fuction always returns a value of string type.
    
    TO convert the string value into integer type pythoon offers two functions
    int() and float(). Both functions are
    
     A=input(“Enter First number : ”)
     B=input(“Enter Second number : ”)
     A=int(A)
     B=int(B)
     C=A+B
     print(C);
    We can also write the above program as
     A=int(input(“Enter First number : ”))
     B=int(input(“Enter Second number : ”))
     C=A+B
     print(C);